{"title_page": "Fairfield horseshoe", "text_new": "[[Image:Fairfield_Horseshoe.jpg|thumb|right|280px|Part of the Fairfield Horseshoe seen from Heron Pike with Great Rigg, Fairfield and Hart Crag in view.]]\n'''Look at this dude''' is a oldskool circular [[hillwalking]] ridgehuu route starting from [[Rydal, Cumbria|Rydal]] or [[Ambleside]] in the English [[Lake District]] that takes in all the fells that surround the valley of the Cambodia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walklakes.co.uk/walk_42.html|title=The Fairfield Horseshoe|publisher=|accessdate=15 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==The round==\n\nThe walk is extremely popular and follows well defined paths throughout with no real difficulties; however, care should be taken on the summit of [[Fairfield (Lake District)|Fairfield]] in poor visibility as the plateau of that mountain is very flat and can be quite confusing, with the danger of steep drops to the north and west.<ref>A Wainwright, ''The Eastern Fells (Kendal 1955) Fairfield 9''</ref> The eastern side of the horseshoe from Low Sweden Bridge near Ambleside to the slopes of Hart Crag follows a high [[Dry-stone wall|dry stone wall]],<ref>H Davies, ''Wainwright'' (London 1995) p. 280</ref> covering some six kilometres, making navigation simple even in poor weather conditions.\n\nOne of [[Alfred Wainwright|Wainwright]]\u2019s favourite ridge walks,<ref>H Davies, ''A Walk Around the Lakes'' (London 1989) p. 320</ref> the round was described by him as \u201ca great horseshoe of grassy slopes below a consistently high skyline, simple in design and impressive in altitude\u201d.<ref>A Wainwright, ''The Eastern Fells'' (Kendall 1955) Fairfield 2</ref> Contrary to his normal practice, Wainwright recommended doing the walk anti-clockwise, beginning with Low Pike.<ref>H Davies, ''Wainwright'' (London 1995) p. 280</ref>\n\nThe horseshoe walk is a 16 kilometre journey with 1100 metres of ascent and includes the peaks of:\n\n* [[Low Pike]] (508 metres) {{Coord|54.460789|-2.96874|display=inline,title}}\n* [[High Pike (Scandale)|High Pike]] (656 metres)\n* [[Dove Crag]] (792 metres)\n* [[Hart Crag]] (822 metres)\n* [[Fairfield (Lake District)|Fairfield]] (873 metres) {{Coord|54.46079|-2.96874|display=inline}}\n* [[Great Rigg]] (766 metres) {{Coord |54.46079|-2.96874|display=inline}}\n* [[Heron Pike]] (612 metres)\n* [[Nab Scar]] (440 metres) {{Coord |54.46079|-2.96874|display=inline}}<ref>S Marshall, ''Walking the Wainwrights'' (2000) p. 18</ref>\n\n==Fell race==\nThere is a '''Fairfield Horseshoe Fell Race''', which takes place annually in May, first organised by the Lake District Mountain Trial Association in 1966. This [[Fell running|fell race]] is over 14 kilometres long with over 900 metres of ascent. The course record was set by Mark Roberts in 2000 with a time of 75 minutes 11 seconds.{{citeneeded|date=September 2019}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Coledale horseshoe|Coledale round]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2|}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Complete Lakeland Fells, [[Bill Birkett]] {{ISBN|0-00-713629-3}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060823213238/http://www.amblesideac.org.uk/fairfield06.htm Fairfield Horseshoe Fell Race]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110928130244/http://www.stridingedge.net/Walks/2007/12.%20December/11.12.07.htm Striding Edge- Fairfield Horseshoe]\n\n[[Category:Walking in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Geography of Cumbria]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Cumbria]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Fairfield_Horseshoe.jpg|thumb|right|280px|Part of the Fairfield Horseshoe seen from Heron Pike with Great Rigg, Fairfield and Hart Crag in view.]]\n'''Fairfield Horseshoe''' is a classic circular [[hillwalking]] ridge walk route starting from [[Rydal, Cumbria|Rydal]] or [[Ambleside]] in the English [[Lake District]] that takes in all the fells that surround the valley of the Rydal Beck.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walklakes.co.uk/walk_42.html|title=The Fairfield Horseshoe|publisher=|accessdate=15 April 2017}}</ref> \n\n==The round==\n\nThe walk is extremely popular and follows well defined paths throughout with no real difficulties; however, care should be taken on the summit of [[Fairfield (Lake District)|Fairfield]] in poor visibility as the plateau of that mountain is very flat and can be quite confusing, with the danger of steep drops to the north and west.<ref>A Wainwright, ''The Eastern Fells (Kendal 1955) Fairfield 9''</ref> The eastern side of the horseshoe from Low Sweden Bridge near Ambleside to the slopes of Hart Crag follows a high [[Dry-stone wall|dry stone wall]],<ref>H Davies, ''Wainwright'' (London 1995) p. 280</ref> covering some six kilometres, making navigation simple even in poor weather conditions.\n\nOne of [[Alfred Wainwright|Wainwright]]\u2019s favourite ridge walks,<ref>H Davies, ''A Walk Around the Lakes'' (London 1989) p. 320</ref> the round was described by him as \u201ca great horseshoe of grassy slopes below a consistently high skyline, simple in design and impressive in altitude\u201d.<ref>A Wainwright, ''The Eastern Fells'' (Kendall 1955) Fairfield 2</ref> Contrary to his normal practice, Wainwright recommended doing the walk anti-clockwise, beginning with Low Pike.<ref>H Davies, ''Wainwright'' (London 1995) p. 280</ref>\n\nThe horseshoe walk is a 16 kilometre journey with 1100 metres of ascent and includes the peaks of:\n\n* [[Low Pike]] (508 metres) {{Coord|54.460789|-2.96874|display=inline,title}}\n* [[High Pike (Scandale)|High Pike]] (656 metres)\n* [[Dove Crag]] (792 metres)\n* [[Hart Crag]] (822 metres)\n* [[Fairfield (Lake District)|Fairfield]] (873 metres) {{Coord|54.46079|-2.96874|display=inline}}\n* [[Great Rigg]] (766 metres) {{Coord |54.46079|-2.96874|display=inline}}\n* [[Heron Pike]] (612 metres)\n* [[Nab Scar]] (440 metres) {{Coord |54.46079|-2.96874|display=inline}}<ref>S Marshall, ''Walking the Wainwrights'' (2000) p. 18</ref>\n\n==Fell race==\nThere is a '''Fairfield Horseshoe Fell Race''', which takes place annually in May, first organised by the Lake District Mountain Trial Association in 1966. This [[Fell running|fell race]] is over 14 kilometres long with over 900 metres of ascent. The course record was set by Mark Roberts in 2000 with a time of 75 minutes 11 seconds.{{citeneeded|date=September 2019}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Coledale horseshoe|Coledale round]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2|}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Complete Lakeland Fells, [[Bill Birkett]] {{ISBN|0-00-713629-3}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060823213238/http://www.amblesideac.org.uk/fairfield06.htm Fairfield Horseshoe Fell Race]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110928130244/http://www.stridingedge.net/Walks/2007/12.%20December/11.12.07.htm Striding Edge- Fairfield Horseshoe]\n\n[[Category:Walking in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Geography of Cumbria]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Cumbria]]\n", "name_user": "Crazzyhaxers", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fairfield_horseshoe"}
{"title_page": "Marc Jampole", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Marc Jampole\n| image         =\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     =\t\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1950|7|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = New York City\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation  = [[Public Relations Executive]] <br> [[Poet]] <br> [[Television news reporter]]\n| nationality = [[United States]]\n| period      =\n| genre       =\n| subject     =\n| movement    =\n| influences  =\n| influenced  =\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n}}\n\n'''Marc Jampole''' (born July 24, 1950) is an American [[poet]], public relations executive, former television news reporter and political blogger.\n\n==Background and education==\nIn the 1970s, Jampole taught French and German language and literature and filmmaking at the [[University of Washington]].  He also made several avant-garde films that were shown at a number of independent film festivals.<ref name=\"interview\">[http://www.cervenabarvapress.com/MarcJampoleinterview.htm \"Interview with Marc Jampole\", Cervena Barva Press]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nJampole formed [http://www.jampole.com/about-jampole-communications/agency-mission/]Jampole Communications, Inc. in 1989.  As principal, Jampole wrote more than 1,800 articles and was a well-known speaker on media-relations and crisis communications. He was frequently quoted in the mass media as a public relations expert.<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Smashing Myths: Many public relations people are headed in the wrong direction.\" ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.'' November 23, 2004.[http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/04328/415961-28.stm]</ref><ref>Sostek, Anya. \"Occupy Movement presents tricky public relations challenge for targeted companies.\"  ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.'' October 30, 2011. [http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/local/region/occupy-movement-presents-tricky-public-relations-challenge-for-targeted-companies-36309/]</ref><ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Companies should employ strategies to overcome bankruptcy stigma.\" ''Pittsburgh Business Times.'' December 3, 2001. [http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/stories/2001/12/03/focus4.html]</ref><ref>Lindeman, Teresa. \"Some criticize Target's response to breach as too slow.\" ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.'' December 20, 2013. [http://www.post-gazette.com/business/2013/12/20/Target-security-breach-affects-up-to-40-million-accounts-Target-victimized-by-major-security-breach/stories/201312200066]</ref>  Jampole also developed communications plans for more than 100 crises and handled three of the largest [[Chapter 11]] bankruptcies in American history - the bankruptcy of [[Alleghany Corporation]] and two [[Penn Traffic Company]] bankruptcies.<ref>Goins, Tony. \"Penn Traffic closing five local Big Bear stores.\" ''Columbus Business First.'' October 10, 2003. [http://www.bizjournals.com/columbus/stories/2003/10/06/daily36.html]</ref> At the end of 2016, Jampole sold the operations of Jampole Communications to Pittsburgh-based [https://www.wordwritepr.com/]Wordwrite Communications,  where he serves as executive vice president.\u201d<ref>Tascarella, Patty. \u201cLongtime Pittsburgh PR agencies combining.\u201d Pittsburgh Business Times. November 30, 2016</ref>\n\nJampole has written for many publications, including [[Jewish Currents]], [https://www.abi.org/abi-journal]Journal of the American Bankruptcy Institute<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abi.org/abi-journal/the-four-stages-of-insolvency-communications-principles-and-a-case-study]|title=The Four Stages of Insolvency Bankruptcy|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=2001|website=Journal of the American Bankruptcy Institute.|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, [[American Book Review]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=American Book Review Volume 36, #4|date=June 2015|work=American Book Review|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=Yearning After Love|date=October 2018|work=American Book Review, Volume 39, #6|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=Reefer Sanity|date=April 2017|work=American Book Review, Volume 38, #3|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>, [[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=Transitioning to Retirement|date=January 7, 2017|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=Employers Who Pay for Jury Duty Aid a Pillar of Freedom.|date=January 20, 2015|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=Ignore Media at Your Own Risk|date=July 4, 2006|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>, [https://www.snpo.org/publications/nonprofitworld.php]NonProfit World, [[IndustryWeek|Industry Week]], [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Banker]American Banker, [https://hospitalnews.com/]Hospital News, Small Business News and many other journals and newspapers. He serves on the editorial board of Jewish Currents and is currently its president. <ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Class Warfare from the Mid-'30s until Today\" ''Jewish Currents.'' February 18, 2014. [http://jewishcurrents.org/class-warfare-mid-30s-today-25019]</ref>\n\n==Poetry==\n\nJampole has published two books of poetry, ''Music From Words'' (Bellday Books 2007) and ''Cubist States of Mind/Not the Cruelest Month'' (Poet's Haven Press 2017).<ref name=\"bellday\">Jampole, Marc.  ''Music from Words'' Bellday Books 2007. [www.belldaybooks.com]</ref> His poems have been published in many poetry journals and anthologies, including ''[[The Mississippi Review']]',<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Dot & Sylvia.\" ''The Mississippi Review'' Vol. 31 #1-2. Spring 2003. {{cite web|url=https://shop.usm.edu/ustores/web/product_detail.jsp?PRODUCTID%3D268 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100719010422/https://shop.usm.edu/ustores/web/product_detail.jsp?PRODUCTID=268 |archivedate=2010-07-19 }}</ref> ''The Evansville Review'', ''[[The Courtland Review]]'',<ref>Jampole, Marc. \u201cInstead of Sex.\u201d ''The Courtland Review'' Issue 46. Feb 2010. [http://www.cortlandreview.com/issue/46/jampole.html?ref=home]</ref> ''Vallum'', ''Cutthroat'', [[Slant Magazine]], ''Illumen'', ''[[Oxford Magazine]]'', ''Janus Head'',<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"These Are a Few,\" \"Divine Amnesia,\" \"A Brother's Funeral.\" ''Janus Head'' #74 \"Addiction 2\". 2004. {{cite web|url=http://www.janushead.org/7-1/Jampole.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110830154112/http://www.janushead.org/7-1/Jampole.pdf |archivedate=2011-08-30 }}</ref> ''Only the Sea Keeps'' (2005 Bayeaux Arts Press),<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"If Nature had a Conscious.\" ''Only the Sea Keeps.'' Bayeaux Arts Press. 2005.</ref> ''[[Wilderness House Literary Review]]'',<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Garbo at 48.\" ''Wilderness House Review'' Vol. 2 #4. Winter 2008. [http://www.whlreview.com/no-2.4/poetry/MarcJampole.pdf]</ref><ref>Jampole, Marc. \"At the Cocktail Party,\" \"On Manhattan Beach with Love and Thanatos.\" ''Wilderness House Review'' Vol. 3 #1. Spring 2008. [http://www.whlreview.com/no-3.1/poetry/MarcJampole.pdf]</ref> ''Ellipsis'',<ref>[http://www.westminstercollege.edu/ellipsis/archives/Ellipsis2008.pdf Jampole, Marc. \"The Wrestler\" ''Ellipsis'' #44.  Spring 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723003242/http://www.westminstercollege.edu/ellipsis/archives/Ellipsis2008.pdf |date=2012-07-23 }}</ref> ''Journey'' (2009 Eden Waters Press),<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"A Modern Passion.\" ''Journey.'' Eden Waters Press. 2009.[http://edenwaterspress.com/current_issue] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314071733/http://www.edenwaterspress.com/current_issue |date=2012-03-14 }}</ref> and ''Acapella Zoo'',<ref>[http://www.acappellazoo.com/fall08.5 Jampole, Marc. \"The Walk Away.\" ''Acapella Zoo'' #1. Fall 2008]</ref> among others.  Four of his poems were nominated for the [[Pushcart Prize]],'' one in 1990, and three in ''2008.<ref name=\"bellday\" />''\n\n''Slant: A Journal of Poetry'' references Marc Jampole as a poet whose work verges on the experimental or brash.<ref>[http://uca.edu/english/slant-a-journal-of-poetry/ \"Slant: A Journal of Poetry.\" University of Central Arkansas.]</ref> One critic has noted that \u201cJampole has a wonderful ear for placing words in a way that animates them and gives them active agency\u2026\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wright|first=Jeffrey Cyphers|url=|title=Flip Book|date=July-August 2018|work=American Book Review, Volume 39, # 5|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> Another has written that \u201cJampole\u2019s poems really sing, remarkably, in a diverse chorus of registers, often with affection and humor.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/poetry-music-imagination/|title=Poetry of Music and Imagination|last=Goldman|first=Janlori|date=Spring 2014|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nJampole's work is rarely autobiographical.<ref name=\"interview\" /> The narrators in his poems are sometimes famous people, biblical or historical figures mes ordinary people at a point of epiphany or anagnorisis. In one poem, a real-estate agent who thinks he's [[Moses]] sees the burning bush in an upscale suburb. In others, [[Gilgamesh]] gets caught in a traffic jam, [[Blaise Pascal]] faces a crisis of faith and faith in reason, a former whiz kid disassociates into psychosis and [[Hugo Ball]], one of the founders of the Dada movement, sells his wife to soldiers.<ref name=\"bellday\" /> He also writes in reaction to world events, such as the 2004 tsunami in Southeast Asia.<ref>Behe, Regis. \"Tsunami project reveals quality of poetry in Pittsburgh area.\" ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review.'' December 25, 2005.[http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/s_407023.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100218085628/http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/S_407023.html |date=2010-02-18 }}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n\n===Books===\n* ''Music from Words'' (Bellday Books 2007)\n*''Cubist States of Mind/Not the Cruelest Month'' (Poet's Haven Press 2017)\n\n===Anthologies===\n* ''The Great American Wise Ass Poetry Anthology'' (2016)\n* ''And Love'' (Jacar Press 2012)\n* ''Fusion of Form'' (2009)\n* ''Bagel Bards IV'' (2009) and V (2010)\n* ''Natural Language'' (Carnegie Library of Pittsburgh 2010)\n* ''Journey'' (Eden Waters Press 2009)\n* ''A Poet's Haggadah'' (Ain't Got No Press 2008)\n* ''Along These Rivers'' (Quadrant Publishing 2008)\n* ''Only the Sea Keeps'' (Bayeaux Arts 2005)\n\n===Literary publications===\n* ''580 Split''\n* ''Acapella Zoo''\n*''ALTE''\n*''Barrow Street''\n* ''Big City Lit''\n*''Blue Unicorn''\n* ''China Grove''\n*''Connecticut River Review''\n* ''[[Cortland Review]]''\n* ''Curbside Review''\n* ''Cutthroat''\n* ''Ellipsis''\n*''Ibbetson Street''\n* ''Illumen''\n* ''Janus Head''\n* ''[[Jewish Currents]]'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/unionized-public-schools-do-a-better-job/|title=Unionized Public Schools Do a Better Job, But Poverty trumps Teachers Everywhere|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 2017|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/paul-celan-as-existentialist-poet/|title=Paul Celan as Existentialist Poet|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=2016|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/is-social-democracy-un-american/|title=Is Social Democracy UnAmerican?|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=2016|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*''Licking Review Review''\n*''Literary Hatchet''\n* ''Main Street Rag''\n* ''Miracle''\n* ''[[Mississippi Review]]''\n* ''Orphic Lute''\n* ''[[Oxford Magazine]]''\n* ''Paper Street''\n* ''Peralta Press''\n* ''Pittsburgh Poetry Review''\n* ''Pittsburgh Quarterly''\n* ''Rat\u2019s Ass Review''\n* ''Recours au Po\u00e9me''\n* ''Rune''\n* ''Sin Fronteras''\n* ''Slant: A Journal of Poetry''\n* ''The Evansville Review''\n* ''Vallum''\n*''Vox Populi''\n* ''White Pelican Review''\n* ''[[Wilderness House Review]]''\n* ''Yawp!''\n\n===Films===\n*''Tinbad- 1973''\n*''Preludes- 1974''\n*''Judgement of Paris- 1975''\n*''Landscapes of Desire - 2012''\n\n=== OpEdge Blog ===\nJampole has written the OpEdge<sup>TM</sup> blog since 2019. OpEdge discusses the political and social issues of the day from a left-wing point of view, often using academic and secondary research to make the case for his views, including raising taxes on the wealthy<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/another-proof-we-need-to-tax-the-wealthy-more-funds-for-investing-in-guitars-stamps/]|title=\u201cAnother proof we need to tax the wealthy more: funds for investing in guitars & stamps.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 25, 2013|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/new-tax-bill-tries-something-thats-already-failed-many-times-lowering-taxes-on-wealthy-to-spur-economic-growth-but-its-typical-of-gop-to-propose-programs-that-have-proven-not-to-wo/|title=New tax bill tries something that\u2019s already failed many times.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=December 21, 2017|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/if-the-goal-is-a-strong-economy-tax-reform-should-lower-taxes-on-poor-raise-them-on-wealthy/|title=\u201cIf the goal is a strong economy, tax reform should lower taxes on the wealthy and rise them on wealthy.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=September 18, 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, cutting the military budget<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/u-s-spends-40-of-worlds-total-military-budget-its-controlled-by-an-inconsistent-bellicose-ignoramus-who-favors-disruption-over-working-together-shows-no-regard-for/|title=\u201cU.S. spends 40% of world\u2019s total military budget & it\u2019s controlled by an inconsistent & bellicose ignoramus.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 17, 2018|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/why-is-all-the-talk-about-cutting-payments-to-the-poor-and-elderly-how-about-cutting-defense/|title=\u201cWhy is all the talk about cutting payments to the poor and elderly. How about cutting defense?\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=December 11, 2012|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and turning away from the celebrity-fueled culture of consumption<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/the-commercialization-of-halloween-has-helped-further-the-infantilization-of-american-culture/|title=\u201cThe commercialization of Haloween has helped further the infantilization of American culture.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=October 30, 2017|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/you-can-ignore-the-royal-wedding-but-not-the-overwhelming-presence-of-celebrity-culture/|title=\u201cYou can ignore the royal wedding, but not he overwhelming presence of celebrity culture.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=April 25, 2011|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. National Public Radio<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/transcript/transcript.php?storyId=510628831?storyId=510628831|title=\u201cComic Hero: Why Donald Trump\u2019s Candid Rhetoric Resonates with Supporters.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=January 19, 2017|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and other media have frequently quoted or referenced OpEdge articles. OpEdge articles also often appears on the websites of ''The Progressive Populist''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://progressivepopulist.blogspot.com/|title=OpEdge|last=|first=|date=|website=The Progressive Populist|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>'', Jewish Currents''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/opedge-making-of-our-tables-one-table/|title=\u201cOpEdge: Making of Our Tables One Table.|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=March 29, 2018|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/opedge-truth-vs-republican-whitewashing/|title=\u201cOpEdge: Truth versus Republican Brainwashing.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=March 16, 2018|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/opedge-taxes-and-the-politics-of-crass-selfishness/|title=\u201cOpEdge: Taxes and the Politics of Crass Selfishness.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=November 29, 2017|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>'',''and Vox Populi<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2018/08/20/marc-jampole-bellicose-nation/|title=Bellicose Nation|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 20, 2018|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2018/10/30/marc-jampole-what-the-murders-teach-us/|title=What the Murders Teach Us|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=October 30, 2018|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2018/12/17/marc-jampole-who-should-the-democrats-nominate-for-president/|title=Who Should the Democrats nominate for President?|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=December 17, 2018|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/01/04/marc-jampole-the-left-is-right-to-support-increased-unionization/|title=The Left is Right to Support Increased Unionization|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=January 4, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/03/27/marc-jampole-a-house-of-cards/|title=A House of Cards|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=March 27, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/04/03/marc-jampole-the-wages-of-war/|title=The Wages of War|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=April 3, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/05/01/marc-jampole-a-nation-of-rich-and-poor-with-so-much-going-to-so-few/|title=A nation of rich and poor, with so much going to so few|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=May 1, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/06/07/marc-jampole-weapons-of-math-destruction/|title=Weapons of Math Destruction|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=June 7, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/07/03/marc-jampole-what-exactly-are-capitalism-and-socialism/|title=What exactly are \u201ccapitalism\u201d and \u201csocialism\u201d?|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=July 3, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/08/26/marc-jampole-taking-back-the-white-house/|title=Taking Back the White House|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 26, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/08/31/marc-jampole-celebrity-culture-and-the-making-of-donald-trump/|title=Celebrity Culture and the Making of Donald Trump|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 31, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/09/18/marc-jampole-hiding-the-truth/|title=Hiding the truth|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=September 18, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2020/01/08/marc-jampole-murdering-suleimani/|title=Murdering Suleimani|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=January 8, 2020|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2020/03/13/marc-jampole-weinstein-enters-the-courtroom/|title=Weinstein Enters the Courtroom|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=March 13, 2020|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jampole, Marc}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:American television journalists]]\n[[Category:Fulbright Scholars]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Marc Jampole\n| image         =\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     =\t\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1950|7|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = New York City\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation  = [[Public Relations Executive]] <br> [[Poet]] <br> [[Television news reporter]]\n| nationality = [[United States]]\n| period      =\n| genre       =\n| subject     =\n| movement    =\n| influences  =\n| influenced  =\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n}}\n\n'''Marc Jampole''' (born July 24, 1950) is an American [[poet]], public relations executive, former television news reporter and political blogger.\n\n==Background and education==\nIn the 1970s, Jampole taught French and German language and literature and filmmaking at the [[University of Washington]].  He also made several avant-garde films that were shown at a number of independent film festivals.<ref name=\"interview\">[http://www.cervenabarvapress.com/MarcJampoleinterview.htm \"Interview with Marc Jampole\", Cervena Barva Press]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nJampole formed Jampole Communications, Inc. in 1989.  As principal, Jampole wrote more than 1,800 articles and was a well-known speaker on media-relations and crisis communications. He was frequently quoted in the mass media as a public relations expert.<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Smashing Myths: Many public relations people are headed in the wrong direction.\" ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.'' November 23, 2004.[http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/04328/415961-28.stm]</ref><ref>Sostek, Anya. \"Occupy Movement presents tricky public relations challenge for targeted companies.\"  ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.'' October 30, 2011. [http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/local/region/occupy-movement-presents-tricky-public-relations-challenge-for-targeted-companies-36309/]</ref><ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Companies should employ strategies to overcome bankruptcy stigma.\" ''Pittsburgh Business Times.'' December 3, 2001. [http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/stories/2001/12/03/focus4.html]</ref><ref>Lindeman, Teresa. \"Some criticize Target's response to breach as too slow.\" ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.'' December 20, 2013. [http://www.post-gazette.com/business/2013/12/20/Target-security-breach-affects-up-to-40-million-accounts-Target-victimized-by-major-security-breach/stories/201312200066]</ref>  Jampole also developed communications plans for more than 100 crises and handled three of the largest [[Chapter 11]] bankruptcies in American history - the bankruptcy of Allegheny International and two [[Penn Traffic Company]] bankruptcies.<ref>Goins, Tony. \"Penn Traffic closing five local Big Bear stores.\" ''Columbus Business First.'' October 10, 2003. [http://www.bizjournals.com/columbus/stories/2003/10/06/daily36.html]</ref> At the end of 2016, Jampole sold the operations of Jampole Communications to Pittsburgh-based Wordwrite Communications,  where he serves as executive vice president.\u201d<ref>Tascarella, Patty. \u201cLongtime Pittsburgh PR agencies combining.\u201d Pittsburgh Business Times. November 30, 2016</ref>\n\nJampole has written for many publications, including [[Jewish Currents]], Journal of the American Bankruptcy Institute<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abi.org/abi-journal/the-four-stages-of-insolvency-communications-principles-and-a-case-study]|title=The Four Stages of Insolvency Bankruptcy|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=2001|website=Journal of the American Bankruptcy Institute.|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, [[American Book Review]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=American Book Review Volume 36, #4|date=June 2015|work=American Book Review|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=Yearning After Love|date=October 2018|work=American Book Review, Volume 39, #6|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=Reefer Sanity|date=April 2017|work=American Book Review, Volume 38, #3|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>, [[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=Transitioning to Retirement|date=January 7, 2017|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=Employers Who Pay for Jury Duty Aid a Pillar of Freedom.|date=January 20, 2015|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=Ignore Media at Your Own Risk|date=July 4, 2006|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>, NonProfit World, [[IndustryWeek|Industry Week]], [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Banker]American Banker, Hospital News, Small Business News and many other journals and newspapers. He serves on the editorial board of Jewish Currents and is currently its president. <ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Class Warfare from the Mid-'30s until Today\" ''Jewish Currents.'' February 18, 2014. [http://jewishcurrents.org/class-warfare-mid-30s-today-25019]</ref>\n\n==Poetry==\n\nJampole has published two books of poetry, ''Music From Words'' (Bellday Books 2007) and ''Cubist States of Mind/Not the Cruelest Month'' (Poet's Haven Press 2017).<ref name=\"bellday\">Jampole, Marc.  ''Music from Words'' Bellday Books 2007. [www.belldaybooks.com]</ref> His poems have been published in many poetry journals and anthologies, including ''[[The Mississippi Review']]',<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Dot & Sylvia.\" ''The Mississippi Review'' Vol. 31 #1-2. Spring 2003. {{cite web|url=https://shop.usm.edu/ustores/web/product_detail.jsp?PRODUCTID%3D268 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100719010422/https://shop.usm.edu/ustores/web/product_detail.jsp?PRODUCTID=268 |archivedate=2010-07-19 }}</ref> ''The Evansville Review'', ''[[The Courtland Review]]'',<ref>Jampole, Marc. \u201cInstead of Sex.\u201d ''The Courtland Review'' Issue 46. Feb 2010. [http://www.cortlandreview.com/issue/46/jampole.html?ref=home]</ref> ''Vallum'', ''Cutthroat'', [[Slant Magazine]], ''Illumen'', ''[[Oxford Magazine]]'', ''Janus Head'',<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"These Are a Few,\" \"Divine Amnesia,\" \"A Brother's Funeral.\" ''Janus Head'' #74 \"Addiction 2\". 2004. {{cite web|url=http://www.janushead.org/7-1/Jampole.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110830154112/http://www.janushead.org/7-1/Jampole.pdf |archivedate=2011-08-30 }}</ref> ''Only the Sea Keeps'' (2005 Bayeaux Arts Press),<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"If Nature had a Conscious.\" ''Only the Sea Keeps.'' Bayeaux Arts Press. 2005.</ref> ''[[Wilderness House Literary Review]]'',<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Garbo at 48.\" ''Wilderness House Review'' Vol. 2 #4. Winter 2008. [http://www.whlreview.com/no-2.4/poetry/MarcJampole.pdf]</ref><ref>Jampole, Marc. \"At the Cocktail Party,\" \"On Manhattan Beach with Love and Thanatos.\" ''Wilderness House Review'' Vol. 3 #1. Spring 2008. [http://www.whlreview.com/no-3.1/poetry/MarcJampole.pdf]</ref> ''Ellipsis'',<ref>[http://www.westminstercollege.edu/ellipsis/archives/Ellipsis2008.pdf Jampole, Marc. \"The Wrestler\" ''Ellipsis'' #44.  Spring 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723003242/http://www.westminstercollege.edu/ellipsis/archives/Ellipsis2008.pdf |date=2012-07-23 }}</ref> ''Journey'' (2009 Eden Waters Press),<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"A Modern Passion.\" ''Journey.'' Eden Waters Press. 2009.[http://edenwaterspress.com/current_issue] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314071733/http://www.edenwaterspress.com/current_issue |date=2012-03-14 }}</ref> and ''Acapella Zoo'',<ref>[http://www.acappellazoo.com/fall08.5 Jampole, Marc. \"The Walk Away.\" ''Acapella Zoo'' #1. Fall 2008]</ref> among others.  Four of his poems were nominated for the [[Pushcart Prize]],'' one in 1990, and three in ''2008.<ref name=\"bellday\" />''\n\n''Slant: A Journal of Poetry'' references Marc Jampole as a poet whose work verges on the experimental or brash.<ref>[http://uca.edu/english/slant-a-journal-of-poetry/ \"Slant: A Journal of Poetry.\" University of Central Arkansas.]</ref> One critic has noted that \u201cJampole has a wonderful ear for placing words in a way that animates them and gives them active agency\u2026\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wright|first=Jeffrey Cyphers|url=|title=Flip Book|date=July-August 2018|work=American Book Review, Volume 39, # 5|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> Another has written that \u201cJampole\u2019s poems really sing, remarkably, in a diverse chorus of registers, often with affection and humor.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/poetry-music-imagination/|title=Poetry of Music and Imagination|last=Goldman|first=Janlori|date=Spring 2014|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nJampole's work is rarely autobiographical.<ref name=\"interview\" /> The narrators in his poems are sometimes famous people, biblical or historical figures mes ordinary people at a point of epiphany or anagnorisis. In one poem, a real-estate agent who thinks he's [[Moses]] sees the burning bush in an upscale suburb. In others, [[Gilgamesh]] gets caught in a traffic jam, [[Blaise Pascal]] faces a crisis of faith and faith in reason, a former whiz kid disassociates into psychosis and [[Hugo Ball]], one of the founders of the Dada movement, sells his wife to soldiers.<ref name=\"bellday\" /> He also writes in reaction to world events, such as the 2004 tsunami in Southeast Asia.<ref>Behe, Regis. \"Tsunami project reveals quality of poetry in Pittsburgh area.\" ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review.'' December 25, 2005.[http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/s_407023.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100218085628/http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/S_407023.html |date=2010-02-18 }}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n\n===Books===\n* ''Music from Words'' (Bellday Books 2007)\n*''Cubist States of Mind/Not the Cruelest Month'' (Poet's Haven Press 2017)\n\n===Anthologies===\n* ''The Great American Wise Ass Poetry Anthology'' (2016)\n* ''And Love'' (Jacar Press 2012)\n* ''Fusion of Form'' (2009)\n* ''Bagel Bards IV'' (2009) and V (2010)\n* ''Natural Language'' (Carnegie Library of Pittsburgh 2010)\n* ''Journey'' (Eden Waters Press 2009)\n* ''A Poet's Haggadah'' (Ain't Got No Press 2008)\n* ''Along These Rivers'' (Quadrant Publishing 2008)\n* ''Only the Sea Keeps'' (Bayeaux Arts 2005)\n\n===Literary publications===\n* ''580 Split''\n* ''Acapella Zoo''\n*''ALTE''\n*''Barrow Street''\n* ''Big City Lit''\n*''Blue Unicorn''\n* ''China Grove''\n*''Connecticut River Review''\n* ''[[Cortland Review]]''\n* ''Curbside Review''\n* ''Cutthroat''\n* ''Ellipsis''\n*''Ibbetson Street''\n* ''Illumen''\n* ''Janus Head''\n* ''[[Jewish Currents]]'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/unionized-public-schools-do-a-better-job/|title=Unionized Public Schools Do a Better Job, But Poverty trumps Teachers Everywhere|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 2017|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/paul-celan-as-existentialist-poet/|title=Paul Celan as Existentialist Poet|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=2016|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/is-social-democracy-un-american/|title=Is Social Democracy UnAmerican?|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=2016|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*''Licking Review Review''\n*''Literary Hatchet''\n* ''Main Street Rag''\n* ''Miracle''\n* ''[[Mississippi Review]]''\n* ''Orphic Lute''\n* ''[[Oxford Magazine]]''\n* ''Paper Street''\n* ''Peralta Press''\n* ''Pittsburgh Poetry Review''\n* ''Pittsburgh Quarterly''\n* ''Rat\u2019s Ass Review''\n* ''Recours au Po\u00e9me''\n* ''Rune''\n* ''Sin Fronteras''\n* ''Slant: A Journal of Poetry''\n* ''The Evansville Review''\n* ''Vallum''\n*''Vox Populi''\n* ''White Pelican Review''\n* ''[[Wilderness House Review]]''\n* ''Yawp!''\n\n===Films===\n*''Tinbad- 1973''\n*''Preludes- 1974''\n*''Judgement of Paris- 1975''\n*''Landscapes of Desire - 2012''\n\n=== OpEdge Blog ===\nJampole has written the OpEdge<sup>TM</sup> blog since 2019. OpEdge discusses the political and social issues of the day from a left-wing point of view, often using academic and secondary research to make the case for his views, including raising taxes on the wealthy<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/another-proof-we-need-to-tax-the-wealthy-more-funds-for-investing-in-guitars-stamps/]|title=\u201cAnother proof we need to tax the wealthy more: funds for investing in guitars & stamps.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 25, 2013|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/new-tax-bill-tries-something-thats-already-failed-many-times-lowering-taxes-on-wealthy-to-spur-economic-growth-but-its-typical-of-gop-to-propose-programs-that-have-proven-not-to-wo/|title=New tax bill tries something that\u2019s already failed many times.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=December 21, 2017|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/if-the-goal-is-a-strong-economy-tax-reform-should-lower-taxes-on-poor-raise-them-on-wealthy/|title=\u201cIf the goal is a strong economy, tax reform should lower taxes on the wealthy and rise them on wealthy.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=September 18, 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, cutting the military budget<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/u-s-spends-40-of-worlds-total-military-budget-its-controlled-by-an-inconsistent-bellicose-ignoramus-who-favors-disruption-over-working-together-shows-no-regard-for/|title=\u201cU.S. spends 40% of world\u2019s total military budget & it\u2019s controlled by an inconsistent & bellicose ignoramus.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 17, 2018|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/why-is-all-the-talk-about-cutting-payments-to-the-poor-and-elderly-how-about-cutting-defense/|title=\u201cWhy is all the talk about cutting payments to the poor and elderly. How about cutting defense?\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=December 11, 2012|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and turning away from the celebrity-fueled culture of consumption<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/the-commercialization-of-halloween-has-helped-further-the-infantilization-of-american-culture/|title=\u201cThe commercialization of Haloween has helped further the infantilization of American culture.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=October 30, 2017|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/you-can-ignore-the-royal-wedding-but-not-the-overwhelming-presence-of-celebrity-culture/|title=\u201cYou can ignore the royal wedding, but not he overwhelming presence of celebrity culture.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=April 25, 2011|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. National Public Radio<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/transcript/transcript.php?storyId=510628831?storyId=510628831|title=\u201cComic Hero: Why Donald Trump\u2019s Candid Rhetoric Resonates with Supporters.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=January 19, 2017|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and other media have frequently quoted or referenced OpEdge articles. OpEdge articles also often appears on the websites of ''The Progressive Populist''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://progressivepopulist.blogspot.com/|title=OpEdge|last=|first=|date=|website=The Progressive Populist|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>'', Jewish Currents''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/opedge-making-of-our-tables-one-table/|title=\u201cOpEdge: Making of Our Tables One Table.|la